description: The Rutgers chapter of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) would like to invite you all to our Fall 2025 General Interest Meeting happening on Thursday, September 11th, from 7:30 pm to 9:00 pm in RWH-206.   As a professional chapter, we host companies for info sessions, go on field trips, organize a civil and environmental engineering career expo, and so much more! All majors are welcome!   Join us to hear from our two competition teams, Steel Bridge and Concrete Canoe, along with presentations by AREMA (American Railway and Engineering Maintenance-of-Way Association) and EIA (Engineers in Action)!    We will also have members of the Civil Engineering Department's Industry Advisory Board (IAB) present about civil engineering and the different sub-disciplines.     Come join us for a fun and informative interest meeting! We will have pizza and cookies as well!    In the meantime, stay in touch with us on our GroupMe and Instagram.

description: Want to study abroad in Italy? We are offering an in-person information session (with free snacks!) at the Rutgers Global-Study Abroad conference room at 102 College Ave. The Director of Umbra Institute, Dr. Zach Nowak, will be joining us from Italy to answer any of your questions. It will start with a general presentation about studying abroad and the Umbra Institute, but most of the time will be allotted for questions and snacking. At Umbra, you can earn direct Rutgers credit for a wide range of fields, including:  Psychology Music, Fine Arts, & STEM Italian Language at any level (beginner to advanced) Food & Sustainability in the heart of the Mediterranean Innovative iCourses for intermediate Italian speakers—seminars in literature, media, and sociology taught in English with hour-long sections exclusively in Italian! Independent Research with distinguished faculty or direct enrollment at the Università di Perugia for advanced speakers  Explore Umbra’s full course catalog here. LEARN MORE AND APPLY HERE!
name: Study Abroad in Italy - Information Session

description: Join the BOLD Center at Douglass as we host our annual career conference! The Christiana Foglio DC'84 Douglass Career Conference is designed to empower students through career planning, discuss topics related to the workforce, and meet other professionals in a variety of industries to share their wealth of knowledge. Learn tips and tools for starting your career, how to navigate networking and interviewing, and the best ways to make your mark in the workplace. With a special focus on doing good work, we will also be hosting a packing party at the conference this year to donate items to community partners in need.  There will be food, giveaways, prizes, and networking opportunities.

description: Stop by Douglass Library to experience a solo exhibition of artwork by the 2025-2026 Lebowitz Artist-in-Residence, Liz Collins, on view September 2 through March 13! Collins is a Brooklyn based artist that works across art and design. She is known for her innovative multimedia fabric, knitwear, and textile work, along with the fashion label she created.   Don't miss out—RSVP today and join the Center for Women in the Arts at Douglass to view the exhibition during a reception and for a talk by artist Liz Collins on October 16, from 5:00 to 6:30 PM! All are welcome! The Estelle Lebowitz & Anne Beneduce-Lebowitz Artist-in-Residence Lecture Schedule: 5:00-5:30pm Exhibition viewing & reception (light refreshments served)5:30-6:30pm Artist’s talk   This experience counts towards the Douglass Discovery curriculum requirement. R3: Career/Discovery/Professional Development/Research.Reminder: To receive DRC curriculum credit, you must complete a reflection survey. Photo credit: Marco Giugliarelli
location: Douglass Library: Mabel Smith Douglass Room & Mary H. Dana Women Artists Series Galleries

description: RU looking to enhance your Rutgers experience with social, academic, professional, and personal experiences to build your leadership and support network? Still looking to find your community within Rutgers? Douglass Residential College provides unique events and opportunities through hands-on research, student organizations, paid experiences, and free travel! By adding a feminist lens to your education, Douglass inspires you to examine inequality, center women’s lived experience in your exploration of the world, and embolden women’s leadership. We welcome you to learn about The Douglass Experience over brunch at the Kathleen W. Ludwig building on the Douglass campus where you will hear from current Douglass students, faculty, and staff, make new friends, and explore the beautiful Douglass campus!  *this event is for RU students who recently transferred and are interested in Douglass, as well as current RU students at any point in their RU career up to the first semester of their junior year*
name: Douglass Residential College Transfer and Interested Student Brunch
organizationName: Enrollment, Scholarship, Housing and Commuter Engagement at Douglass Residential College at Douglass Residential College - DRC

description: Join us for our annual 5K Run and Mile Walk! Whether you run, walk, volunteer, or cheer from the sidelines, help us raise awareness and support the fight against lung cancer. All proceeds are donated to Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center to support lung cancer research efforts. Interested in walking or running? Register here on our website!   Interested in volunteering? Join our GroupMe!   The first 200 participants (walker or runner) will receive a free Wawa hot beverage coupon upon check-in! The first 50 early 5K registrants will receive a free t-shirt! Food, beverages, raffles, and games will be included!
name: Lung Cancer Awareness 5K Run and Mile Walk
